<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901226-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>901226-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Thailand's Copyright   Enforcement Inquiry   Is Initiated by U.S.</HL><DATE>12/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 10</SO><CO>   FREST</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. initiated an investigation ofThailand's copyright enforcement practices, U.S. TradeRepresentative Carla Hills said.   The investigation under U.S. trade laws was begun Fridayin response to a petition filed by organizations representingU.S. copyright interests and alleging piracy of U.S. movies,music and other copyrighted works.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We have repeatedly expressed our strong concern to Thaiofficials at all levels that the rights of U.S. copyrightholders are not adequately safeguarded,&quot; Mrs. Hills said.&quot;Unfortunately, we have seen no improvement in Thailand'swillingness to shut down the considerable illegal copying ofU.S. movies, music, books and computer software, or to ensurethat U.S. companies obtain prompt and effective redressthrough Thailand's legal system.&quot;   Mrs. Hills said, &quot;Thailand's stake in improving protectionis considerable, both in terms of attracting desired foreigninvestment and ensuring that its own artists andentrepreneurs receive fair compensation for their efforts.&quot;   The U.S. is seeking to schedule prompt consultations withthe Thai government on the issues raised in the petition.</TEXT></DOC>